formatted_address: 350 Tenth Ave Suite 1000, San Diego, CA 92101, USA
text:
Initially, the product sounds great - on paper.

Then you get into the contract, and Regus is completely unfair. Even malicious. They charge without permission, overcharge, slam you with fees for printing, meetings, and even coffee, and even charge after your contract ends. Though the staff at this particular location is very nice, the office product they sling is surrounded with hidden contingencies - addenda and clauses favorable to only them.

The latest example of this is them charging me $349/mo. for three months AFTER my contract ends for what they 'Business Continuity Service'. Calling to inquire, they told me this fee is for them to hold onto my mail (??!!!? Not deliver it to me, just hold on to it)

Chance after chance over nearly two years, Regus has proven their true colors. If you want to double-pay for office space, go here. If you want something fair, reasonable, and more-professional in a nicer building, check out Symphony Towers - the 33rd floor.

Regus, treat people as you want to be treated. Shame on you.

text: Absolutely love this space! Well designed, adaptable, community-oriented, and a true value San Diego. Utilizing this space during the day offers awesome natural light, comfortable climate, and plenty of options for work space. The events that I have attended have been very well curated and thoughtful. I especially love how the furniture layout can accommodate anything from collective mastermind groups at a large shared table, to quiet meetings in a private room. Even beyond a great aesthetic, "You Belong Here" builds upon and strives to support the community assets that have long existed in City Heights and San Diego at large. Well done!

text: LOVE THIS SPACE! I rented the photography studio for a few hours to knock out a product shoot for a local company. Getting in was easy (hello automated unlocking system), the space was super clean and the upgrade for gear rental was awesome! Tons of natural light shines through the large windows and countless cute little nooks can be found all over the space. Can’t wait to go back for another project!

formatted_address: 3619 El Cajon Blvd, San Diego, CA 92104, USA
text: What an amazing community to be a part of!  Besides the use of their well-lit photo space and uber convenient, gorgeous space to host  workshops, the community is incredible.  Due to their thoughtful planning of high-quality events, the caliber of people it draws to the space is not something that can replicated in a coffee shop.  I have met a number of fellow small business owners there and have created a network of allies that have given me the extra help I need to tackle my work.

formatted_address: 3619 El Cajon Blvd, San Diego, CA 92104, USA
text:
The large windows and natural light all day long is a nice benefit of using this space. I loved using it for some natural light work, and also work where I rented their studio strobes and light modifiers.

They have a kitchen with a sink, coffee maker/espresso machine, fridge and microwave. Full size restroom for changing needs, comfortable couches, and an abundance of electrical outlets and USB charging outlets which is convenient for everyone! It's just a comfortable space to be in.

It's the perfect size for an event as well. I held an event there with roughly 20 people and there was plenty of room for more! There's also an excellent Ethiopian restaurant two doors down called Addis Market!

formatted_address: 3619 El Cajon Blvd, San Diego, CA 92104, USA
text: We recently held an event at You Belong Here and the hospitality was enormous!! Nic and Stacy who run the space are hardworking and genuine. It's  to refreshing to see a space ran by women and Nic and Stacy are crushing it. They went out of their way to assist in the process of arranging the space during the event and took the time to having meaningful conversations and connections with us from the jump. Before the event they even reached out to their community to cross promo and it worked very well.  I recommend anyone looking for a cool co-working space, or event space to visit You Belong Here and join their culture. They also have great community events where myself and my team learned about how to improve our entrepreneurial skills and connections. You Belong Here is a beautiful location and a great place to meet people.

business_name: Regus - California, San Diego - Liberty Station
formatted_address: 2305 Historic Decatur Rd Suite 100, San Diego, CA 92106, USA
text:
Absolutely abysmal. The office space itself is nice, the location is great and the parking is ample. 

The challenge is finding anyone with any type of customer service or communication skills. Their billing is extremely dreadful. They make lots of mistakes, and when they do, they don't just credit you back. Instead, they make you pay the entire invoice (including the mistake) and then will credit you back the following month. It doesn't sound like it's an issue until you find  yourself tracking down bunches of accounting and billing mistakes. 

No one at the center or regional positions can resolve any challenges or issues that come up. They refer you to the "help desk" (it's anything but helpful). No one can resolve your issue and when you ask to escalate to a  manager, they tell you it'll be 24-48 hours. Then weeks go by and no manager ever calls you back.

Essentially, when I terminated my lease, the manager at the center (at the time) suggested that i sign up for a 3-month mail forward service. I thought it might be a good idea for 1 month, but she said you have to sign up for 3. So i did. 

Then when i got my 3rd bill, I sent a note to cancel, because i didn't want to renew for another term. It went unanaswered and I forgot about it. Then i got another bill for the following month, so i called to cancel. Weeks went by and i got a call that said i had to cancel on line. So i logged in to cancel and the only button to click was "next" and the system inadvertently extended me for another 3 months..

SOOOOO... I called to have them reverse it - and they WONT. OMG are you kidding me? What kind of ridiculous organization is this? Then i try to escalate and can't get any help. Just a phone call from the front desk telling me that i have to pay.

There are soooo many other options for executive office space. My strong recommendation is to not use Regus. They are beyond awful.

business_name: Regus - California, San Diego - Emerald Plaza
formatted_address: 402 West Broadway Suite #400, San Diego, CA 92101, USA
text: You can get charged up to 200% of your contract every month here. And here is why: I think it would be ideal for Regus to fully disclose its brand: Regus- The Hidden Fees Company. (I am not being very creative  :D) So let me give you a good glimpse of what you are about to sign up for: hidden fees. I have been here for a a few months now and every single month the rent (and it is not really a rent because they are not a real estate company. They are a membership company and they compare themselves to a gym membership) is different and you get charged for things you wouldn't really expect. For example, I was granted permission to move in 4 days earlier than my lease term which was nice but then their IT had charge me 4 x $12/day for internet usage because I had setup my computer and plugged it in their wall internet. I found out that the usage of their kitchen was not initially included in the lease amount and I was being charged an additional $10/day for kitchen use. You can opt out of it and not go to kitchen. LOL They also tell you that you have a phone line that you can use but then there are a variation of minute by minute charges depending, I think, on which US zip code you call. So for example one domestic call had cost me $7.56 Basically the same thing you get for free on your cellphone, they charge you for it. And then you get charged a tax amount (not really clear to me what the percentages are) on top of every variation of the charge. So by my calculations, if you are a busy business owner, making a bunch of calls every day, you can really pay up to twice as much as you initially thought you had the office for. The building has conference rooms but you have to pay a minimum of $65/hr for a conference room which is basically a small room with a few chairs a table. They are more impressive meeting rooms for $110/hr. The conference rooms are not available over the weekends. I am pretty sure there are a whole bunch of other hidden charges that I have not yet come across but I wouldn't be surprised if I see a charge for over usage of internet above 5GB :D or some other ridiculous thing. Do yourself a favor and find another company. I am being very honest with you and sharing my objective experience here. The one star is a bear minimum of the ranking and that goes to their nice and super friendly staff.

formatted_address: 7250 Dallas Pkwy #400, Plano, TX 75024, USA
text: If you like good design and ample natural light, you'll love this space. The community manager is incredibly warm and welcoming, just like the space, and really takes pride in making everyone feel comfortable while working. They provide a mix of different daily breakfasts throughout the week from healthy to less, healthy but delicious, like breakfast tacos - so everyone is happy! There is also a generous snack platter daily. Not to mention unlimited local coffee, loose leaf tea, La Croix and sodas. There are tons of different little community workspaces and there are so many plants speckled throughout the space, which make me very happy. They even give you a succulent upon joining! I like the different types of events hosted in the space to help network with other members from other offices. Some are purely social, like the weekly happy hour, while others, like lunch and learns, were educational and informative. The teams are very professional and polite and I love learning about all of the other businesses in the space.

text:
The positives are: great venue, great events, and cross-Texas access.

The primary negative is that there are well-known "fakers" that have infiltrated the mentor and speaker networks. People that claim to have experience, successes, and credentials. The same people that you see at other startup events, and you know they are lying. People claiming large exits, important government positions, CEOs of successful companies, and so on. 

Spend more time making sure these people are who and what they claim before endorsing and entrusting them. For example, you should look at GovCity, McNutt Silicon Valley Growth Syndicate, J Vittorrio Law Firm, Neighborhood Goods, Q 51, Imprint, T Wildcatters, Sumo Ventures, GlassHeel, and DSV. Not at all what they claim to be.

formatted_address: 333 West San Carlos Street Riverpark Tower, San Jose, CA 95110, USA
text:
When it came time to look for some new office digs, WeWork was a no brainer. Due to our distributed workforce the model suits our needs perfectly.

Don't tell any of my out-of-town coworkers but I happen to think WeWork Riverpark Tower is our best WeWork location (sorry not sorry). We moved into our suite on February 1 and while there was still some some construction punch list items outstanding and it wasn't without bumps in the road, all items were handled with professionalism and speed by Laura and her team. The resolution of issues vs. the absence of issues is what I rate service received on. By that standard, the service received here is top notch.

 The WeWork Riverpark Tower team (at every level) work so hard to make the experience of working here seamless and do it all with a smile. They love to hear feedback on how things can be improved and they implement the very best ideas. The fellow members and the Community Team come up with great, creative events which makes it a pleasure to come to work on a daily basis.

The design is great - WeWork is know for their design and I appreciate that the latest design also integrates wider hallways to make the entire office feel more open. 

I recommend checking this location out!

text:
Don't walk, RUN AWAY! 

I never write reviews but I need to warn others, as the owners are crooks. If I could I would give ZERO stars

Here are a few of the highlights of this place: 

1. Kiss your deposit goodbye...
2. Re-read the contract, because what they say and what is written is completely different, the lease is month to month, but they will randomly change it to yearly if you are not careful.
3. The wall are so thin, I could hear the guy next door sipping his coffee.
4. The office rent is $500- 750 per month, but I over heard neighbor complaining that the contact sent was $1200 per month. they refused to change and where FORCING him to pay and stay 1 year!!! ( LIKE I SAID THE OFFICE WALLS ARE SO THIN)
4. They are always in constant breach of contract -The Internet in the building was consistently slow and unreliable 
5. Only 1 building has a receptionist. My building has no-one...so random people walk around trying to open the office doors. 
6. The package/ mail room is not secure so anyone can take your packages. And even in the main lobby, there is just rarely someone there. Just a screen that dials some random number that no one picks up. 
7. They will access your private office without notice and take things. They took the blinds from my office 

Like I said, RUN

text: Excellent workshop, makerspace for Startups, Builders and Makers. You can make ANYTHING here. For such a small person, she has amazing strength and knows how to use her arms and hands for the perfect amount of pressure. I highly recommend you see her.

Yesterday, I switched up and got a massage from Will. IT WAS INCREDIBLE! As soon as he started, I could immediately tell that I would enjoy it. I have a hard time finding a massage therapist who knows how much pressure to use and let me tell you, Will had the perfect amount of pressure consistently through out my massage. A quarter of the way through I could feel my entire body was relaxed and the tense muscles in my shoulders had finally been relieved of their strenuous duty. When the massage was finished, I was in awe over how relaxed I really was. I stayed on the bed for an additional 5 minutes just to soak in this feeling of serenity that was so new and foreign to me. I literally felt like I was on cloud nine. 

BOOK NOW! You won't regret it.

text:
Good for shared co-op but very crowded at times. On Mondays and Tuesdays it is the worst. During the lunch time the pantry is noisy so people sitting near to the pantry may not like it and we are glad we took a room instead of open tables.

Parking is always full if you reach by 9:30/10:00 but there is extra parking in the adjacent building which can use and that is cool.

formatted_address: 20 S Santa Cruz Ave #300, Los Gatos, CA 95030, USA
text:
Yes, yes, and YES!! A professional environment with a positive work focused energy that encourages productivity. Previously, I was working out of my home office and contemplating if I would really use a shared workspace. I was weighing all the reasons such as drive time, membership costs, etc. After a month of considering it I finally said what the heck why not try it and find out.

I signed up for a free 1-day pass and in the first hour I accomplished more then I was in an average day at home. Wow! I sat there and thought, "That 1-hour of work just 'paid' for a month of membership - SIGN ME UP!" 

I SIGNED UP AFTER AN HOUR OF BEING THERE & I AM SO HAPPY I DID! 
 
The Office manager (Suzi) is amazing at what she does. She genuinely cares about her members and goes above and beyond to help them to enjoy the environment where they work. From surprise treats in the members kitchen, *Muffin Mondays*, to networking events and social hours. 

I am lucky I found this awesome community for business professionals. Try it out - it might just be the key to your success!

text: I love The Satellite Los Gatos. Everyday when I walk in the front door I feel relaxed and ready to accomplish all my goals in this bright and open space.  I've been here for just about a year now and I love all the members and also all the wonderful clients who walk in from all over the world!  If you are searching for a quiet space to get some work done with a professional atmosphere and close to all the wonderful restaurants and shops nearby this is the place for you!

formatted_address: 20 S Santa Cruz Ave #300, Los Gatos, CA 95030, USA
text: The Satellite Los Gatos is amazing! They have everything that you could want in an office. Great location, nice clean, modern facilities, and great people to work and network with. The location is nice and central so there are plenty of places to eat and get coffee nearby, but you don't even have to go out for coffee since Satellite provides it for you free, anyway. The staff is incredibly helpful, using the space any time of day is super easy and I just cannot say enough good things about this place! Try it out and see!

formatted_address: 20 S Santa Cruz Ave #300, Los Gatos, CA 95030, USA
text: As so many people already know Downtown Los Gatos is a special place. Full of charm, locally owned shops and boutiques, and great food. This beautiful town nestled amongst the redwoods at the foothills of the Santa Cruz Mountains leaves you wanting for nothing. The Satellite Los Gatos is lucky enough to be right in the heart of the action, across from the Downtown Plaza Park, surrounded by a vibrant community and great events. If you are tired of commuting to San Jose every day, or are sick of working at home by yourself, you should definitely stop by and give this workplace community a try. A great staff with a wonderful coworking community makes The Satellite my favorite place to work in Los Gatos.

formatted_address: 19925 Stevens Creek Blvd #100, Cupertino, CA 95014, USA
text:
I've had an office in the Pacific Business Center (Cupertino) for a few years and thought it was time to give it a review.

As I think about the staff at this location, I can without hesitation ascribe to them the highest level of professionalism I've observed in this type of setting. All of my interactions with them have been courteous, respectful and any commitments quickly followed-up. They are efficient and appear to enjoy working here and project that to clients.

I feel welcome when I walk in the door... amazing how that makes a difference in your day. They call me by name and when appropriate will inquire how I'm doing.

The Center is for the most part very quiet - I can get work done here day or night

The place is very clean and well maintained -- the offices, conference rooms, restrooms, even the break room where there is constant coffee preparation is clean.

The infrastructure services; Internet/network connections, telephone system, receptionist, mail distribution, security, air conditioning -- it all works and I don't have to think about it(!)

My hat is off for Pacific Business Center Cupertino - they deserve all five stars.

We are able to quickly and easily schedule meeting rooms that are clean/quite/comfortable space with all the technology needed to stay connected. Whether we need a conference room for 10 or a small room meeting room for 2, PWS has what we need. We have storage lockers to keep samples/demos/literature and can print any additional materials on their high end printers. We also receive/ship many samples/parts effortlessly thru Fed Ex/UPS. formatted_address: 2700 W Anderson Ln #205, Austin, TX 78757, USA
text:
Start up life can be a grind and especially in a dynamic market like Austin where real estate is at a premium. My company has been so lucky to find a home within Link Co-Working where the staff is remarkable, helpful and feel like an extension of our team providing resources that you I would have to hire multiple people to provide. 

The facilities and spaces are stunning with high quality desks and seating, private meeting rooms that are  easy to self book and manage your own schedule and space needs. Our clients feel at home in our Link space and the meeting spaces provide the perfect foundation for successful brainstorming and strategic planning sessions.

They keep the coffee hot, the wifi on point and often surprise and delight members with snacks and events, speakers, parties on a regular basis. They work hard each and every day to create an authentic community of like minded business leaders killing it day in and day out to drive business performance. At Link, you aren't in it alone.

The success stories coming out of the thought leaders at Link are limitless, its fun being in the mix with companies and entrepreneurs at every stage of their growth and I have to believe that the environment the Link provides plays a key part in the success of all of our businesses.

Come by, check it out, have a cup of coffee and you will see why co-working not only works but helps remote workers and leading brands be the best version of themselves we can be each and every single day and achieve big things.

text:

Then I found Link. I just recommended this place to a fellow entrepreneur who lives in coworking places and I'm going to keep recommending this place. 

Note – They have new management and they've started investing in better coffee, more amenities, and a bigger team of super friendly staff.

text: First of all, If you are not white be prepared to feel unwelcome. text: I cannot recommend Industrious Austin highly enough. Over the past couple years that my firm has been working out of their space, we've always felt that it's *our* space. formatted_address: 201 W 5th St #1100, Austin, TX 78701, USA
text: While I have only been here a month, I am a big fan of Industrious. When I moved to Austin I toured three different co-working spots and found Industrious to be the best of them all. They have mastered the balance of social interaction and productivity. As an accountant, I have found it to be the perfect spot where I can interact with people but also zone in and get my work done. The common areas are never noisy so they provide a great work space option if you need to step away from your desk. What really makes it is the friendly staff -- Sarah Lawton has made me feel right at home!

formatted_address: 201 W 5th St #1100, Austin, TX 78701, USA
text: I've had an office in Industrious for the last two years and it's a great place to work. Friendly staff, convenient downtown location and breakfast options daily help me stay productive every day of the week.

formatted_address: 201 W 5th St #1100, Austin, TX 78701, USA
text: Industrious has definitely exceeded my expectations of a co-working space.  Since they cap the number of members it ends up being an excellent balance of social interaction and productivity.  I often find myself in the open spaces working and feel comfortable taking important phone calls.  In a busier coffee shop/public space/even a place like WeWork that’s a bit busier, I feel uncomfortable leaving my laptop at a desk to take a phone call.  I always feel comfortable at Industrious and especially appreciate Sarah Lawton for making this office such a welcoming space.

formatted_address: 2110 W Slaughter Ln #160, Austin, TX 78748, USA
text: We were put into a tight spot when our new office was delayed due to construction issues and our current lease expired.  We had 2 weeks to figure out a place to put our 3 staff members so we could continue to run our business.  Luckily I came across Orange! Shelly and Laurie were amazing and my staff loved being there.  They did fun things like birthday pizza Friday, Taco Tuesday, member lunches, etc.  One of my staff members mentioned that Laurie made a point to give you a complement once per day and that really made an impact on her.  My staff was well taken care of and I'm so happy we ended up leasing space there while we waited for our new office to be completed!

formatted_address: 2110 W Slaughter Ln #160, Austin, TX 78748, USA

formatted_address: 2110 W Slaughter Ln #160, Austin, TX 78748, USA
text: Orange is both my office, and my home away from home. Comfortable environment, great coffee, fast internet, awesome parking, HEB next door. It's a quiet working space, but not like a library -- I'm not afraid of answering my phone. Shelley and the gang have made it a great space all around.

formatted_address: 2110 W Slaughter Ln #160, Austin, TX 78748, USA
text:
Yeah, internet is good, facilities are good, etc. etc. All basics, check. Ample and free parking, next to HEB, UPS, Subway and a few other useful things.

This is a family business, ran with love, and it shows. Shelley, Dean and Laurie are here pretty much all the time and Shelley (founder) and Laurie (COO) run the place, and they are super open to feedback, ideas and suggestions regarding the place or how it can fit withing the larger community. Or to just chat! It's a two-way street too, don't be surprised if Shelley pulls you in the kitchen to ask about this new idea she has for the space. There is a real sense of community,  broader activities (not just perks for members), and I have started some good friendships here, so many good conversations.  It's very chill. At this point in time, it is not crowded.

text: Such an amazing find. They seem to have thought of everything and from the first moment it felt like my work-home away from home. I didn't think I needed a co-working space until I found MELD. formatted_address: 502 W 30th St, Austin, TX 78705, USA
text: About a year and a half of working from home got me to start looking for a co-working space that had a flexible pricing structure and a central location. My productivity was plummeting until I found MELD. The environment is friendly but not distracting and it has everything that I need of a co-working space: large extended screen monitors, standing desks, coffee, snacks, booths for private phone calls, offices for collaboration with colleagues and a quiet, noise machine equipped, sequestered upstairs area when the task at hand requires particular focus.  Totally worth it!

formatted_address: 502 W 30th St, Austin, TX 78705, USA
text: I love MELD!!! The staff is so nice & welcoming! I appreciated the tour they offered. The accommodations cover everything you need, from conference rooms, quiet rooms, adjustable desks, snacks, mail service, etc. I especially enjoyed working in their 'Focus' room; my creative juices flowed, I WAS focused and able to be very productive. I love the decor - may be a minor thing to some but being a visual person, MELD is so welcoming and just a very cool place & environment to work. I can't recommend MELD enough!!!

I highly recommend MELD if you're looking for a place to focus on work away from home, give presentations, or take conference calls.

formatted_address: 2400 E Cesar Chavez St #208, Austin, TX 78702, USA

formatted_address: 2400 E Cesar Chavez St #208, Austin, TX 78702, USA
text:
I’ve hosted a variety of events at Atmosphere and am always wowed by what the space can do. I’ve hosted small group breakout sessions, board game nights (great and small), happy hours, brunch, and even a three day, multiple venue, conference with Atmosphere serving as my largest venue. The design of both the actual physical space and the furniture allow for SO many configurations, I can’t believe the number of ways I’ve played tetris to serve radically different needs and different layouts. And, I’ve flipped the room from a conference venue to a happy hour in less than an hour…magic! Perhaps the greatest magic of all is that it doesn’t feel like “just a space,” it does as the name suggests, it’s creates an “atmosphere” that permeates all of the events I’ve ever created there.

Photo credit: Ashlee Newman Photography (Brunch picture)

formatted_address: 701 Brazos St, Austin, TX 78701, USA
text:
I am ashamed for having worked out of here for almost two years and not giving this place a 5-star review. (The psychology of complacency...am I right?) 

Being here at Capital Factory has given me more value than I could ever imagine. 

When I first came here in 2017, I'll be honest...my startup was doing well, but it was not making a lot of money. So it wasn't such an easy decision to invest in a space like this. But it has made such a big difference in my day to day life. I FEEL like coming to work. I feel inspired. I know I can meet good people to make my business run successfully. 

Coming here, I knew very little about the tech scene, but I knew that I could meet tech-minded people who can grow my business. Since then, I've partnered with a programmer and a data scientist who have developed tools for my clients to improve their lives. We are currently working on artificial intelligence software that helps my clients write better resumes to land them their dream job.

In the last two years, my company's revenue has 5x'd. And no, I'm not giving ALL the credit to Capital Factory...it takes a $##! ton of hard work and consistency to get there, but sometimes I wonder how far I really would have gone if I had still been working from home. There is something about the energy of this place that makes me want to keep going. 

I need to give a massive shout out to the hard working staff that works here. They are all unbelievable. Not going to exclude anyone because there are too many people that make this place run successfully, but the entire staff is absolutely fantastic. Praise the operations and FRONT DESK team on all floors (1, 5, 8, and 16) because I feel absolutely welcome every moment I step in this place. No matter what they are getting, they deserve a raise. I love each and every one of them.

formatted_address: 11801 Domain Blvd 3rd Floor, Austin, TX 78758, USA
text:
I left WeWork recently because of an issue of racial profiling that would have put myself and my staff and potential clients at risk that they shouldn't be subject to.

Sadly, no matter the facts, they just aren't interested in making changes that they say they're open to. They refer to their diversity programs but how are those programs really impactful if you can harass people like me and subject them to a clear double standard and furthermore the staff and management not take responsibility?

In the end, since God has blessed me to be an employer, I could have done two things...go take legal action and spend resources and time for something that was a dicey situation or make a bigger power move, move my company and future business to someone else. I chose the latter.

Sometimes, it's best to just take my business elsewhere and in this instance, I got a better situation where I'm paying more money, but that is money WeWork will never get going forward because of how they decided to mistreat me. That perhaps is the best way to send a message.

I also canceled my membership with Wework Gas Company Tower because of how their New York Corporate executive management handled me. See, they lost two accounts and their rival got more money from me and will continue to get more money long term because of how they decided to speak to me.

Be careful about how you treat customers. Not only did I leave but I wound up giving another company even more money in the short term and long term. Customer service does matter and I can hurt them in their pocketbook without filing a lawsuit.

Just because I'm a black business owner doesn't mean that I don't have the ability to make money or just accept substandard service.

formatted_address: 612 Brazos St, Austin, TX 78701, USA
text: Just left the Refinery after visiting for the day, and I must say, WOW! Warm is the first word that comes to mind. Every woman there was so warm and welcoming--both the team and paying members. I reached out to these gals on Instagram knowing that I would be in town this week and needed a dedicated workspace today. I was worried that if there was no potential of me coming on as a member, they might prefer I not come in. Wrong. No questions asked, they responded quickly and said "yes, girl! come on in for a free trial day!" When I arrived, Gracie greeted me and gave me a tour of the space. Nothing was off limits and I could sit wherever I pleased, which was so nice since some workspaces only offer specific desks, have a million quiet zones, etc. I felt so at home instantly. Later, I desperately needed a phone charger and Gracie (shoutout #2, hey girl!!) gave me hers. Everything was spotlessly clean and no detail was left unnoticed. I would HIGHLY recommend this for any woman in Austin--SO wish I lived here. (Writing this review from around the corner at Royal Blue which was a fabulous recommendation made by Haley when I was on the hunt for a snack, She was also SO sweet and helpful.) Thanks for a great day, gals! Wishing you all the best in 2019! I can't say enough good things.

formatted_address: 411 W Monroe St, Austin, TX 78704, USA
text: We held our wedding at Vuka in January. I already had an awareness of Vuka, which is why I sought it out. It basically comes decorated. That was a big thing for me because I'm not as creative as some people and you don't have to do much work to make it look great. It's a great indoor/outdoor venue with lots of seating and tables already there. They have a "preferred" vendor list but you are welcome to have whatever vendors you'd like. We had noble pig do the catering (also wonderful) and did flowers ourselves. It's so easy to make this place into whatever you want. All of the people we worked with were exceptionally friendly and laid back. I think the vendors appreciated the laid back, yet very professional, approach of the venue also. Everything was in place by the time we showed up to set up, and the whole night went very smoothly. Can't say enough how much we enjoyed holding our big party there. It's nice to have an affordable and accessible place that is centrally located (since it concerned me to have people driving an hour out into the hill country). Guests were able to uber without a problem, and for those who drove, parking is included in the whole package. Thanks to Vuka for having such a nice space 😊

text: I have been taking my dog to Work and Woof for a few months now and it is amazing. My dog loves going there and it is very convenient for me. The staff is wonderful and extremely helpful. I recommend using their services for anyone looking for a doggy day care in the Austin area.

formatted_address: 4930 S Congress Ave building a, Austin, TX 78745, USA
text:

My doggies love going to daycare here- they get to play for 9 hours!! I wish I could take them everyday because they really love it so much. The only thing I wish was better, was report cards. It takes awhile to get them, if I get them at all. I know y’all are so busy though (when I get there to drop dogs off at 7:45 there are already 20 dogs there) so I can understand the delay. I just wish I got them because I love seeing the report cards.
There’s an indoor and outdoor park, it’s byob. Biscuit and Lana love their new daycare! Thanks guys

formatted_address: 4930 S Congress Ave building a, Austin, TX 78745, USA
text: I used to manage a dog day care so I am specific where I bring my dog. Work and Woof has been nothing but wonderful. All of my friends bring their dogs here & I love that our dogs get to play! Thank you Jill & Work and Woof.

formatted_address: 4930 S Congress Ave building a, Austin, TX 78745, USA
text:
Let me start with idea of doggy daycare took me a long time to consider.  When my husband and I moved here, we had gotten jobs that had long hours and we are unable to give our corgi the amount of time she needed to be fully exercised.  We started bringing her to another daycare in the area and at first she loved it, but after awhile of going, she would come home and still have an exuberant amount of energy. It became frustrating because we felt she wasn't getting the exercise that she needed and   her energy level would not change, regardless of her going to Daycare.  Come to find out, Penny spent almost half of her day kenneled!  

The reason why Work and Woof is amazing is because she's not kenneled at all. She gets to play all day, take her naps when she wants to, if she even wants to. There are places where dogs can lay down and take a breather.  The best part of the day is watching the videos they post and you can see all of them just napping together! :)

Jill and her staff have become Penny's family and she is so excited to see them every time we pull up to the building, so much so that she pretty much let's herself into the place.  If you have not checked this spot out, you should do so immediately! I'm so happy we found Work and Woof when we did!

text:
The Hive saves us in so many ways routinely. When my husband is out of town and I'm a single parent of a 2 year old and a 10 month old, this is where I go. I always see friendly faces, can grab a bite for the kids and I, a beer for me and have a fun and safe place for them to play. When I have school work to do after work, my husband can always lean on the Hive to help keep us sane. 

Our Saturdays are always spent here for free play, coffee, and a warm breakfast. 

When my husband tires of his at home office and needs a refreshing place to work, he jets to the Hive even without the kids.

You seriously can't go wrong in trying them out. We use a lot of what they have to offer, and yet there's still so much more!

It is indeed such a wonderful village to have.

text:
Do yourself a favor check out the reviews on Facebook, and google other reviews to get real reviews for Regus.

If you love receiving hidden charges then you will love Regus. If you love working in the heat you will also love Regus. If you don't care about the items you leave in your office you will love Regus.

I can't speak to all the sides of the buildings, but the side that faces Baptist, gets extremely warm. Around 4 PM it gets up to 81 degrees. Around 6 PM it is around 83-84 degrees. Part of the reason is because they turn off the air conditioning and heating between 5 PM and 9 AM. They keep them turned off during the weekend and which ever holidays they feel like. HOWEVER, you can pay extra to have them turned on.

We asked if there are any issues, or problems because we are a company that will be operating 24/7. We were told no, but I'm sorry this is Florida - how is no AC not a problem nor issue?

Additionally, there management really don't care about your security. We were placed in a temp office until the lease was up on the office we leased. The thing I still don't understand is why we were giving a key to office 407 when it is under lease by someone else?

text:
I would not recommend Regus to anyone.  Although their offices are a good temporary solution to many business models, the time and energy spent trying to decipher their invoice system, along with the unbelievably atrocious staff at the accounting level and above, makes Regus an option I will not select in the future.  If you do decide to use Regus, be sure to keep a close eye on your account, and be quick to ask questions because if an issue goes above the on-site employee's ability it is impossible to get a human being to help.   I am currently MONTHS into trying to retrieve a security deposit for a previous unit, and the only issue they are having is physically sending me the money.  There is no dispute about the charges, only the fact they are not set up to send funds.  Apparently the only option for me to receive my security deposit back is if I fill in an Excel tracker created circa 2002, and then email this old tracker loaded with all of my company bank account information to their accounting department community email address that is shared by at least a dozen Regus employees -- no thank you.  

Another time I had a client drop off an expensive bottle of scotch to the Regus front desk, roughly $250 bottle, that disappeared.  I contacted Regus about it and no one could care less.  
 
The immediate, on-site employees are wonderful.  Once you need to go above them there is no telling if you will even receive a response.

text: Worked here for a while and never had any issues personally, however my co-workers have had various instances of theft by the cleaning services provided. I leave stuff in bags under my desk all the time and it's never been messed with, or thrown out, so why in this particular instance was her bag thrown in the trash? text:
Staff are professional and facility is nice. It is not there nicest location but better than most other businesses in this sector. 

BE VERY CAREFUL. The big issue with Regus always is how bad they treat you when you leave. It's not the local staff it's the corporate headquarters. They gouge you with fees, and crazy charges that make everyone that I have ever met, who's left a Regus, angry and upset. Why they do this is beyond me. Seems like a terrible thing to do to a good customer. But they do it all the time.

 Make sure you read your contract carefully. Do not forget that your contract Auto renews if you do not give them written notice. What happens to many people is their contract gets extended for another 12 months before they even know about it. Then when the conversation comes up they look in their contract and see the clause they never paid attention to previously. They do it on purpose and they do not care that it upsets their customers. 

Their corporate headquarters are run by terrible people. I even had a branch manager that I knew quit because of the unethical things they were demanding that she do regarding pricing and customer charges. They should be ashamed of themselves
 
She was an amazing manager and all the customers loved her but they treated her like garbage. It was awful to see.

text: I had a custom brochure RUSH job to produce on a Sunday.  I went to Office Depot and was treated so rudely by the print and copy employee that I finally quit asking questions and walked out of the store.  Office Max did not have the right paper or binding, FedEx Kinkos was closed.  But I was surprised to walk into Staples in Jacksonville Beach and meet Chris in the print shop there, who had a big smile and was ready to help.  He listened to my request and let me know that they didn't have the paper I needed, nor the binding.  HOWEVER, he showed me other options that would print beautifully.  There was a problem with my PDF document and he called and left a voicemail and also sent an email.  I didn't see them until the next morning.  When I called Staples, I talked to James in the print department, who picked up right where Chris left off and solved my problem and finished the job.  I highly recommend this store's print shop and commend them for their professionalism and willingness to tackle a tough job.  I refuse to patronize a store with lazy and rude employees (that means you, Mr. Rude Dude in Office Depot).

formatted_address: 1617 Park Pl Ave Suite 110, Fort Worth, TX 76110, USA
text:
Unfortunately this location lacks some of the amenities seen at other coworking spaces.  Having visited Ensemble (did not stay) soon decided not the best fit. The engery was a little lack luster and dated. 

Would recommend Common Desk coworking - has a Ft Worth location but also many other locations in the DFW area. This comes in handy if you frequently do business in different areas and like continuity. 

Love how Common Desk thinks outside the box in amenities offered and choosing locations!!  Really.... they pick areas that are alternative, creative, and supportive of a business mindset. Feels like a trendy boutique fully stocked with everything you need to get things done.  

Maybe Ensemble and Common Space just cater to different crowds but Common Space is quickly expanding across DFW so they must be doing something right.

Update: Just seeing the owner response and saddened that they post something untrue based upon a negative review.  Yes, I know a member and had a  brief relationship 19 years ago but 19 years later I seriously doubt I'm intrested in defaming a business over a fling! formatted_address: 4731 Camp Bowie Blvd, Fort Worth, TX 76107, USA
text:
We love craftwork & go all the time, but this morning we were let down by the guy working. We showed up at 7:10am Saturday and noticed the sign wasn’t on. I got out of my car and walked up to the door to open it thinking maybe the guy standing behind the counter looking at me, forgot to turn on the open sign. To my surprise the door was locked. I looked at the hours again and yes on the door it shows they open Saturday at 7am. I sit there until 7:20 thinking maybe, just maybe the guy inside got a late start and will come at least tell me. Nope, by 7:25am he still was standing behind the counter and never once came to the door to say anything to me. Needless to say we left and drove across town to a different coffee shop.
As a former small business owner I would want to know if one of my employees treated customers this way. It would have taken him less than a minute to open the door and let us know what the deal was.

I have been a longtime customer of craftwork since they have opened this location. Unfortunately, every single time that I have come in to this shop over the year; their quality of drinks and the baristas attitudes have worsened. Repeated pretentious behavior by the baristas have left me with an unfortunately unpleasant opinion of the direction that this company is headed. Favorable treatment is definitely observed between employees and “regular “ customers. This same level of care for customers is very much so selective.
There has also been a considerable decrease and inconsistency in the quality of drinks.

formatted_address: 1121 W Magnolia Ave, Fort Worth, TX 76104, USA
text:

The only negative I have on this location is that it is an absolute furnace in the summer during the afternoon. The windows are fantastic, but it's like an oven when the sun starts setting.

text:
WeWork is more than just a co-working space. It’s an amazing culture of people that are putting their heart and soul into their projects. These are people with amazing drive and ingenuity who love communing with each other. 

When you take a community like that and provide them a safe place to grow like the WeWork Clearfork Campus - you get a game-changing set of businesses that are actively making a difference in both the local and national economy while still honoring the local community.

This facility is expertly outfitted to enable growth, creativity and collaboration while respecting the need for quiet and focus. The tailored amenities and furniture help to shape a home-away-from-home that reels you and and gives everyone the freedom to work they way they need to in a place that really takes the grind out of the hustle.

The WeWork staff are welcoming and eager to assist you in growing your business through providing all sorts of accommodation so that you can grow naturally and unhindered. 

When you come to visit, ask for the Brooklyn tour! 

.. just trust me!

text: If you're looking for a great co-working space in the DFW area, just come here and sign up. Save yourself the time of researching other places. text: This is an awesome workplace! It's nice and quiet, always super clean, and the coffee is great!  You get to connect with other companies and learn what they have to offer.  They keep it fun too  :-)  I would definitely recommend this place to anyone looking for office space or to hold meetings !!!

formatted_address: 1090 Texan Trail, Grapevine, TX 76051, USA
text:
The staff are amazing, competent, and always helpful and open to dialogue. The bathrooms are regularly cleaned, and the soaps... wow. Sometimes I want to eat my hands. I am relieved when they switch to pine needle smells and the like. Oh, and they have a shower which I've never seen dirty.
The workspace generally is very quiet, and there are rooms where you can take a call to be considerate of others. It's encouraged to do that, and I personally enjoy going into an open conference room for ten minutes to hash out some details with others when I can.
The community is super nice and incredibly entrepreneurial. I've connected with many "co-workers" here at the comfortable lunch table and accommodating kitchen. Free coffee and granola bars every morning is a huge plus. The monthly taco parties don't hurt either!
Frankly, what more could you want in a co-working space? If the management doesn't change, this place will go far because the nature of the co-working idea lies in constant improvement. Everyone here not only pioneers a field, but also looks to improve their society and self in the process.

formatted_address: 629 N High St 4th Floor, Columbus, OH 43215, USA
text: After working at other co-working spaces around Columbus, I can certainly say that Industrious is top-notch! The staff is so friendly and helpful. Our whole office loves April because of how she goes above & beyond to make our work environment pleasant and enjoyable. There are so many amenities like coffee, soda, happy hours, monthly community lunches... and the list goes on. I highly recommend Industrious to anyone looking for an office space.

formatted_address: 629 N High St 4th Floor, Columbus, OH 43215, USA
text:
Our academic department was in need of a unique space for our annual retreat. We needed something away from home and private, but equipped to help our productivity. April, the community manager, suggested Industrious for the day, and the experience exceeded our expectations.

April's directions for parking were spot on, we had access to amazing culinary choices for our lunch break, and the space was exactly what we needed. She provided snacks, beverages, all necessary hardware to connect to remotely and to present. The restrooms were impeccably clean, the security guards at the entrance very polite, & other long and short term companies and individuals had their own spaces and never infringed on ours. It was rejuvenating to have a new place to help generate new ideas, keep us focused, and enjoy a special part of the city together. 

Industrious in Columbus is highly recommended for a half day, full day, or multi-day space need.

text: Industrious has been a home away from home. April is so thoughtful, kind and is always looking to bring all of the members together in new, fun settings. formatted_address: 45 E Lincoln St, Columbus, OH 43215, USA
text: I've spent nearly 2 years at the Perch, and it has been one of the best things that happened to me in my nearly 30 years of being alive.... the amount of talent, passion and enthusiasm that fills this place, is just amazing! I've worked at various offices across the US and the UK and this was the best office, with the best management and the best co-workers. At the time the job I had did not require me to be physically present at my desk, but I would drive 40miles (one way) just to be amongst some of the most inspiring and smart people (aka other Perch peeps) I've ever encountered! Tracy and Bob make everyone feel so welcome... They are amazing! During my 2 years there I have not met one other member that I didn't like... Everyone is super intelligent, friendly, and most importantly, helpful.. I've gotten advice on so many things that helped me in both professional and personal life. For a person not from Columbus, everyone was super helpful in connecting me with people so I could grow my network, and I know I wouldn't get the same help at other co-working spaces. We had monthly happy hours at local restaurants and bars, the fridge is always stocked with beer and the coffee is amazing (and local!). I highly, highly recommend The Perch. If I ever find myself back in Columbus, I will definitely become a member again. I miss that place every day!

formatted_address: 2997 Indianola Ave, Columbus, OH 43202, USA
text:
Simply Living is a community organization that celebrates and connects people to learning opportunities that promote community sustainability, environmental awareness, and our local economy through educational outreach and partnerships within our community.

Simply Living had shared office space at The Salt Mines during the second half of 2018 after having been located for many years on the second floor of a church [a location that had not been accessible to those who use wheelchairs or have other mobility limitations].

During the six months or so while Simply Living had been sharing space at The Salt Mines, I attended a 12-13-2018 Simply Living Holiday Open House at that location.

For the first time in many years, people who use wheelchairs had been able to attend a Simply Living event at their office location. 

Simply Living has moved again and now shares space at COhatch Worthington [The Library and The Madery], 752 High St., Ste. 2, Worthington, at the northeast corner of the Worthington Village Green.

formatted_address: 2997 Indianola Ave, Columbus, OH 43202, USA
text: I've been a longtime worker at the Salt Mines for many years. It's a great place that emphasizes community and networking. I do freelance web design, and moving out of a home office to the Salt Mines as an office space brought great increases in the amount of work I was able to do. I'd highly recommend it for anyone looking for a co-working space that emphasizes community.

formatted_address: 35 E Gay St, Columbus, OH 43215, USA
text:
One of the nonprofit organizations with which I am involved moved its office recently to Club Level CoWorking. This move represents a cost savings for the nonprofit organization with which I am involved and provides a location at which to store many of our items.

Our monthly public meetings [that usually include a speaker or other program] are held on Saturdays at 12:00 noon. The building is locked on Saturdays, which means that a member of our group must staff the front door to let people into the building and then use a computer chip to allow people onto the elevator so that they will be able to travel to the second floor so that they will be able to enter the Club Level CoWorking suite of rooms and then enter the meeting room.

The bathroom [which is around the corner on the second-floor hallway] requires a three-digit code to enter [which I can understand from a "security" standpoint] but I had been horrified at the end of our meeting to learn that we had been locked into our meeting room [within the Club Level CoWorking suite of rooms] with no means of escape [even to the Club Level CoWorking entrance lobby] unless someone with a computer chip unlocks that door.

formatted_address: 421 W State St, Columbus, OH 43215, USA
text:
While the Columbus Idea Foundry is primarily a co-working space for its members, public events and/or invitation-only events [for non-members] are also held there.

I have attended the three below events, so far, at the Columbus Idea Foundry.

• Columbus Advisory Committee on Disability Issues [CACDI] [2-22-2018]

• Microdosing Psychedelics: A DIY [Do It Yourself] Mental Health Movement [hosted by Mind Manifest Midwest and Cap City Biohackers] 8-27-2018]

• Equality Ohio Stakeholder Summit [9-30-2018]

While definitely a great location for able-bodied people [and there is an elevator between the first floor and the second floor], the Columbus Advisory Committee on Disability Issues [CACDI] quickly learned that the Columbus Idea Foundry is nearly impossible to travel to via public transportation if you are a wheelchair user because Lucas St., a poorly-maintained brick street with intermittent sidewalks on the east side of the building, is nearly impossible to navigate for people who use wheelchairs.

formatted_address: 752 High St Suite 2, Columbus, OH 43085, USA
text:
Simply Living is a community organization that celebrates and connects people to learning opportunities that promote community sustainability, environmental awareness, and our local economy through educational outreach and partnerships within our community.

Simply Living has moved for the second time within the past several months after having been located for many years on the second floor of a church and then briefly at a co-working space at The Salt Mines, 2997 Indianola Ave.

Simply Living now shares space at COhatch Worthington [The Library and The Madery], 752 High St., Ste. 2, Worthington, at the northeast corner of the Worthington Village Green, in a 60-year-old building that is the former location of what is now called the Old Worthington Library.

Simply Living does not have an office at COhatch Worthington but they do hold board meetings and schedule occasional public events at that location. Simply Living has told me that they have now found an ideal location.

I recently [5-13-2019] attended a Simply Living reception in the Kilbourne Room at COhatch Worthington that had included a tour of the building and a brief presentation about the Central Ohio Transition Hub.

The plan had been for that event to be held outside on the patio but it had been raining that day so we had met instead in the Kilbourne Room at the south end of the first floor.

text:
I am a domestic relations attorney that left a firm to start my own office in May of 2019. Looking to moderate my costs, I considered the “virtual office” concept and contacted Office Evolution, among other such businesses. I ended up choosing Office Evolution because they offered more cost effective plans and was located close to my home. It turned out to be the best decision I could have made. Right from the initial meeting, Natalie and Lisa made me feel right at home and basically rolled out the red carpet. They listened to my needs and fit me with a package that allowed me to become profitable almost instantly. They truly cared about me and my business like they were partners. I was blown away. Since that meeting their services have been beyond my expectations and they continue to care as much as the first day. I’d also like to specially thank Natalie that acts more like my employee than OE’s. She always goes above and beyond to make it appear as if this is my exclusive office and if I ever have a question or concern (not often), she personally sees to it that it is answered and that I am satisfied. If you are looking to open an office but want to avoid all the unneeded costs, this is the place and these are the people to align yourself with. 
Douglas A. Kutsko, Esq.

business_name: PS Executive Centers - Office Space Columbus
formatted_address: 1900 Polaris Pkwy #450, Columbus, OH 43240, USA
text:
I used to have a traditional law office with an administrative assistant working in my office.  I felt like I had to work in my office for three reasons:  (1) that's where I received calls, (2) that's where our locally networked office management software was located, and (3) that's where my assistant was working.  

Technology changed my office operation.  With VOIP, I can receive calls at my office number and have them patched to my cell phone wherever I am.  With cloud-based office management software and data storage, my paralegal and I can work from anywhere we have an internet connection.  

Technology changed my office operation, but I still need a place to meet clients, I still need a place to work sometimes, and I need someone to handle inbound phone calls and other administrative tasks.  That place is PS Executive Centers, and that someone is the PS administrative associates. The conference rooms are perfect for meeting clients, the common areas project a professional image appropriate for a law firm, and the day offices are great places to get work done.  The administrative associates effectively handle my incoming calls according to protocol tailored to my needs, and they also assist me with administrative tasks and projects.  

By using PS Executive Centers, I have saved an estimated $15,000 in overhead per year.  For attorneys with solo practices and small firms, I highly recommend PS Executive Centers.

Shawn R. Dominy, Esq.
Dominy Law Firm, LLC

180 Montgomery St #100, San Francisco, CA 94104, USA
text:
WILL CHARGE YOUR CREDIT CARD WITHOUT TELLING YOU

I just wanted to get a cup of coffee and do some work for a couple hours--like I'm able to do at any other cafe in SF. I get that this is a "co-working" cafe, but why is everything is SO UNCLEAR AND CONFUSING?! 

I order my coffee and look for a place to sit. There's a gate and an iPad with some vague instructions to put in your phone number. I follow the steps, and enter my info (including my credit card), all while still completely confused by how this entire setup/model even works. I'm taken to a landing page where I need to enter a seat number. I walk past the gate, type in a number, and sit down.

Next thing I get an email saying that I've been charge $15!! First off, if you're gonna charge me, make that abundantly clear with a check out button--just like every single purchase made on the internet. Second, if I buy a coffee from your cafe, I expect to be able to sit and do at least some work at no added cost. 

I'm completely fine with paying to do work in a clean space with lots of amenities. That said, make your business model clear to your customers! When I walk in, I'm going to treat your cafe like any other in SF; I'm going to order a coffee and look for a place to sit. If your cafe deviates from this norm in any way, it needs to be made crystal clear to your customers!

The offices at SOMACentral are great, spacious, in a nice building with beautiful views, and very reasonably priced. Ken, the owner, is one of the nicest people I’ve met and treated us incredibly well the entire time. Brandy, who works with him, makes sure the place is well run, the kitchen is stocked, and management is very responsive.

After booking out three offices, we finally ran out of room and had to move, but I couldn’t have been happier with our experience at SOMACentral.

649 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
text:
The conference room is beautiful and it's a prime location, but customer service (or lack thereof) is in dire need of revamping. Unfortunately on this visit, customer service amounted to being treated as if we were a nuisance when we tried to get access to the space in the morning. 

There is an overall attitude of attempting to automate everything to remove any human contact, and that coldness comes through clearly should you actually need to interact face to face to get help during your reservation (unless you might be a potential customer for their start up, then they can turn into such nice people curiously quickly, if they think you might be able to help them). 

I had reserved the room at least a month in advance through a 3rd party website (Liquidspace). Suddenly, 24 hours before Liquidspace would charge me I was told by Known Space that I needed to cancel my Liquidspace reservation and book directly through their startup booking company, which seemed highly questionable. 

Overall, if you want to feel like you should keep quiet and be seen but not heard, then this is the place for you. As a customer, I was told when I should arrive and how to do my job (in front of my clients!). If you want to feel like you have a boss in the office and have to to watch your every move to not get in 'trouble' by management, then this is the place for you. 

When I asked for help to access the building in the morning, I was asked to have the other attendees trying to access the conference room to stop calling them. They wouldn't have to call if the building access actually worked! This is not the customer's fault, and acting like it is is very poor customer service.

Previous visits went much better, but this last visit I was treated awfully as a customer.

text:
Love this building! Been here over 3 years. Staff has always been friendly and attentive. They usually greet me by name when I walk in and have been responsive to problems I have. I've hosted events here as well and the staff was more than accommodating. 

The building has an old-SF, industrial motif mixed with modern painted walls/wallpaper you generally see at WeWork buildings. One of my favorite things about it is how nice the light is. I've done some shoots at this location and the sunlight is easy to find. Of course they have blinds if you want to hide from the sun. The location, while Tenderloin, is very convenient. I ride a motorcycle and there are a few locations where you will always find a free parking spot. You usually groups of motorcycles parked nearby. You can't find that further downtown!  

It's located between Civic Center and Powell stations so it's an easy walk on a rainy day. Lots of great eating options as well. A partner company offered our company 6-months of free rent  to relocated to a different WeWork building downtown and we unanimously decided that this building was where we wanted to stay.

formatted_address: 345 California St Suite 600, San Francisco, CA 94104, USA
text:
Preface: I worked at this location (Financial District) of Industrious for one month during a visit to San Francisco in May-June of 2019.

Industrious is a pretty top-notch coworking space. Their interior architecture design, is in my opinion, easily one of the better ones of the coworking spaces in the area. The offices, phone rooms, and common areas are a fair bit more spacious than other popular coworking spaces too. Overall, I feel that Industrious strikes a good balance between liveliness and professionalism when it comes to design.

Compared to the average coworking space, it’s worth pointing out the provision of free snacks (fruits, bread, yoghurts, pop, etc.) and small food related events which are regularly organized; an example of such food events include an ice cream / popsicle event, a whisky and coke happy hour, a popcorn bar event, a DIY yoghurt bar event, and recently for world productivity day an assortment of brain foods. Even if you don’t partake in these food events, it is pretty cool to see events of these types, which take place about 2-3 times a week, as it sort of shows the commitment from Industrious to go the extra mile in adding value for their tenants.

More particularly to this Financial District location of Industrious (I haven’t been to the Embarcadero location), the building (345 California Center) is pretty good looking from the inside and outside, it is equipped with the the new efficient type of elevators where you enter your floor number before you get on the elevator. However the windows on the building are not full wall windows, and since there are tall neighboring buildings, the opportunity for a good view from the office (if that’s important to you) is probably one thing lacking in this space.

The part which stood out to me a lot during my work visit duration at this location of Industrious, was the community management/operations staff. It is hard to convey in a short text based review here the difference for a coworking space, which usually involve additional community interaction through small events and other interactions, between having alright-good staff and having great staff. The current staff whom include Jonathan and Caroline definitely fall under the latter category for me, they’re delightfully cordial and professional. I witnessed a really pleasing environment run by them during my time here.

Overall, I look forward to seeing Industrious expand to more locations in and around the financial district.

So I told him he still has to pay the invoice I was almost done . He said he needed to wait for accounting department but it was closed on the weekend. formatted_address: 353 Sacramento St Suite 1800, San Francisco, CA 94111, USA
text: I've been a SOMACENTRAL customer for over 5 years.  Here at JobScore we operate a small, profitable software company with core of people in San Francisco and a decent sized remote workforce.  Most of us are more experienced folks with years of industry experience.  Candidly, we want to go to work at a place that is about getting work done.  There are no flipping scooters.  There's no craft cold brew.  There's no hipster wardrobe. The people are friendly and the vibe is mostly about GSD. Ef wework. Wewin.  If you are a grown up looking for a well-priced by-the-desk spot for your smaller company - this is the spot.  It's class A office space, there's views and none of the BS you get with with other "perk oriented" co-working facilities and networks.  You are just as likely to hear / interact with people actually selling / supporting customers / doing business here rather than living in a 100% cone of silence.  Somacentral is the spot for business people who want a sweet place to work and get their team together in San Francisco, and has been so over a decade.  The alumni of this place are also a who's who of friggin unicorn companies including twilio, instagram and many more.  If that's the kind of culture you'd like to create, guess where you should be?

formatted_address: 151 Potrero Ave, San Francisco, CA 94103, USA
text:
Please note this review is entirely about customer service and has nothing to do with the venue quality. It may be amazing. I may never know...

I called this venue to confirm my understanding that they book team building events. (They do.) I then asked if it would work for our upcoming company casino party and listed the number of tables we planned to bring. The person on the phone said casino events wouldn't work there. That was fine. Then: 

Me: We do team building activities pretty regularly, so could you tell me what kind of events we could do that *would* work in the space? We may be able to partner up in the future. 

Her: Well, we don't do casino events. 

Me: That's fine. You said you do host team building events. Can you tell me what kind? 

Her: We don't do gaming. We do art things. 

Me: Ok. Could you give me an example of the kind of art things you're talking about? So, could you tell me what another group has done there as their own team building event that worked with the space? 

Her: Art things. That's what we do. Not gaming. 

Me to her then, and to the ownership if they happen to see this review: After VERY clearly understanding our upcoming event isn't a match for your venue, I attempted three times to see if we could book you for the type of event that is a match. It's like pulling teeth and I can't keep trying. I'm sorry that this was my experience of what otherwise looks like a great space.

business_name: Hygge Coworking at The Music Factory
formatted_address: 1000 North Carolina Music Factory Blvd, Charlotte, NC 28206, USA
text:
Our office has been located at Industry Coworking for several years and we have been incredibly happy for a number of reasons:

- The space is amazing. High ceilings. Brick walls. Wood floors. Lots of natural light.

- The location at the NC Music Factory is perfect. It's technically in Uptown so we get the benefits of being in Uptown, but we do not have to deal with so many of the negatives of Uptown. We have free parking and there are ways to get in and out of the Music Factory where you can miss most of the standstill traffic that can make Uptown a nightmare. Plus, the restaurants and bars that share the complex with us are great.

- The fact that it is "coworking" and not just an office with a shared entrance. We regularly work with people who have businesses here to make our smaller marketing agency work like a much bigger one. There are graphic designers, web developers, social media experts, photographers, accountants, and lawyers all here working together. There are also several cool start-ups that we know about before anyone else. Plus, we have gotten a lot of new clients since we work in the B2B marketing industry.

Industry Coworking is all the best things about having an office without any of the drama. It's open 24/7, there are conference rooms to have meetings in, there are people to hang out with, there is free coffee, and free water.

But no one cares what time you get in or when you leave, what you're wearing, or anything that has to do with office politics.

text:
Our office is located in South Charlotte, but we had clients coming in for a conference in Uptown.  We wanted to meet with them in a location that was convenient for them. Upon arrival, the space was beautiful -- on the 27th floor with great views of the city.  David greeted us and let us know that there was food and beverages available.  He took me to our room and helped me get all our tech situated.  We ended up having a super productive meeting and our clients kept commenting about how great the space was.  

I will definitely use Industrious again over any co-working space in Charlotte.  Thanks so much David for all your help!  I look forward to working with you again.

formatted_address: 615 S College St, Charlotte, NC 28202, USA
text:
Ya know, I hate to be that person... but it's actually quite a myth that open workspaces are optimal. Certainly, some circumstances calling for collaboration benefit highly from such an area, but in virtually no career are people going to collaborate 100% of the time. Sure, they have teeny tiny phone booths which can be used when you really need to hunker down and to do some focused work. But you can't reserve them. Not having a space to myself where I am expected to complete my work has become a real problem for me. There are literally no cubicle type walls whatsoever, all of the walls are made out of glass. My productivity has been obliterated. It's impossible for me to focus. Frankly, I'm considering leaving my job because of it. Sure, it's a trendy place to hang out, if you really want to hang out with your coworkers during non-working hours. Sure, they have free beer and fruit water. They DON'T have a cafeteria. That really sucks. Considering that I'm working smack-dab in the middle of downtown, this means that if I don't want to bring my lunch with me every single day, there are no convenient, healthy, or inexpensive options -  all of which will take precious time away from my lunch hour, simply to access. I'm not just trying to trash this place, I'm still giving it three stars for the good things about it. The best thing about WeWork is the friendly and helpful staff. But I cannot simply give full marks for the things that it does indeed lack. Further, I think WeWork is encouraging a dangerous movement in large-scale companies that are increasingly implementing company-wide open office plans - which I believe they will realize is a mistake - in due time. 

When I first toured the facility, one of the first things I noticed when walking down the hallway - is that it caused everyone to stop what they were doing and look up at you as you walked past. If companies cared about productivity, they might be more aware of studies that show that it takes 20 minutes to fully refocus after that kind of interruption. The pressure from management to complete work in an efficient manner has not reduced in correlation with the ability to do so... and that's a real problem.

*Edit:
It's also kind of interesting that I just put it in a three-star review, and yet Google is still reporting that WeWork has 19 five star reviews and no others.

text: Regus deserves a "NO STAR RATING" I have attempted to be patient with Regus but I have lost all confidence in them and can’t wait for the day my contract ends.   They consistently over charge for amenities not used and even after acknowledging the errors are their fault they still refuse to refund the money.  With in the past 5 billing cycles my statement has been wrong every time.  At this point I am waiting out my contact to end and would not suggest anyone do business  with this company.  Please save yourself the grief  and rent somewhere else.  Due to being ignored and overlooked by corporate, at this point all I can do is hopefully prevent others from enduring the frustration and theft in which I have experienced.

formatted_address: 3440 Toringdon Way Suite 205, Charlotte, NC 28277, USA
text: I had a terriable expierence with Regus. The first 2 weeks there was a technical issue which negatively impacted my business as my call volume significantly decreased during that time... essentially the call went to a fast busy signal. Although I reached out to management several times with concerns that I was not receiving calls, the issue was not resolved in a very timely manor.  Once the issue was fixed, clients began making comment that they were not greeted before being forwarded to my direct line or that they thought they had the "wrong number" because they couldn't understand the greeting from the receptionist. On several occasions I called my number to observe for myself that the line was not being answered and when it was answered the greeting was muffled and inaudible. I feel as though I am a reasonable person and could understand there may have been need for an adjustment period, consequently, I was patient throughout the process, trying to give the girls friendly reminders to please talk into the receiver when answering the phone and trying to figure out why the receptionist wasn't answering the phone for extended periods of time during the day. Nevertheless, the situation did not improve. I contacted the supervisor, who was aware of the situation, to express my concerns about the unsatisfactory answering service, technical issues and overall inability to provide the amenity I thought I was paying. I explained that because the issues were not resolved I would no longer be retaining thier services. I had a personal business line forwarded to Regus and consequently withdrew that line. I utilized Regus for less than a month and during that time the line was not working appropriately for two weeks and the service was embarrassing; overall, the negative impact on my business was inexcusable. Due to the circumstances, I requested to be released from my contract, which was approved and I was told I would not accure further charges from that point on. However, I was charged for the following month. When I inquired about the charge I was told it would be refunded. Not only was it not refunded,  I continued to receive invoices for several months. This all happened in September and here it is Febuary. No communication, no refund and a whole lot of clean up on my end. As a buisness owner, I'd advise anyone looking for an answering service to seek elsewhere. There are a lot of great alternative options around Charlotte, it's just not worth it.
